          bigtophero
"></div><p>耶路撒冷——近几个月来，数十万以色列人走上全国街头示威，反对总理本杰明·内塔尼亚胡政府计划的<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/israeli-doctors-go-on-strike-to-protest-netanyahus-judicial-overhaul-463530e7?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">司法改革</a>。</p><p> 7 月 24 日，执政联盟推动以色列议会获得通过，这是该联盟希望通过的一系列<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/israel-netanyahu-government-judicial-overhaul-protests-862dffd3?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">限制法院系统权力的</a>法律中的第一部。在达成妥协的谈判破裂后，该法案在没有任何反对派支持的情况下获得通过。反对派议员走出房间，抵制投票。</p><p>内塔尼亚胡是该国任职时间最长的总理，目前已进入第六个任期，在他的政府于三月份首次尝试通过另一套不同的法案后，内塔尼亚胡使司法立法从失败中恢复过来。在大规模抗议和大罢工导致国家瘫痪后，他<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/strike-called-flights-grounded-in-israel-over-netanyahus-judicial-overhaul-plan-e8c95930?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none" rel="noreferrer noopener">推迟了这项努力</a>，但他在六月份表示，他将以修改后的形式通过这项改革。</p><p>该法律的通过标志着以色列社会的一个关键时刻，可能与该国最高法院摊牌，而该法律旨在遏制该机构的权力。对于数千名表示将退出的<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/israels-judicial-overhaul-raises-security-concerns-as-reservists-refuse-to-serve-5d68bfff?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">预备役军人</a>，以及威胁要大规模停工的商界、工会领导人和医疗专业人员来说，这是一个决定性的时刻。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          bleed
"><div class="media-object-video"><div class="wsj-media-summary clearfix"><div class="strap-container"><h4 class="strap" itemprop="description"></h4></div></div><iframe width="400" height="225" src="https://video-api.wsj.com/api-video/player/v3/iframe.html?guid=B58B7540-4CF9-464C-A04F-C0E71926FD01&amp;height=225&amp;width=400&amp;plid=video_amp&amp;chainVideos=true&amp;parentUrl=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.wsj.com%2Famp%2Farticles%2Fisrael-protests-judicial-overhaul-netanyahu-7e264a71&amp;a=a" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe><p class="imageCaption">以色列医生周二举行罢工，当局在因总理本杰明·内塔尼亚胡政府进行的司法改革而发生骚乱的夜晚，强行将抗议者从道路上带走。照片：阿米尔·利维/盖蒂图片社<span class="imageCredit">
        
        
        </span></p></div></div><p>以色列最大的工会以色列总工会表示，他们正在为可能举行的总罢工做准备，一些抗议者正在敦促其采取这样的行动。然而，工会决定不在第一项法案通过后立即宣布大罢工。</p><p>第一项法案通过的第二天，以色列的医生和医务人员举行了罢工。</p><p>此次改革<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/israeli-judicial-overhaul-pits-secular-religious-communities-against-each-other-a4177c16?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none" rel="noreferrer noopener">引发了该国的分裂</a>，引发了美国等主要盟友的担忧，并在伊朗支持的真主党武装组织沿其北部边境造成的威胁日益加大的情况下，引发了对其军事准备情况的质疑。分析人士警告说，该国可能会陷入宪法危机。</p><p>这是您需要了解的内容。</p><h3>以色列民众为何抗议？</h3><p>在这个拥有 900 万人口的国家，每个周末都有多达 50 万以色列人出来抗议内塔尼亚胡<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/netanyahu-advances-overhaul-of-top-israeli-court-drawing-thousands-of-protesters-ee0287d7?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">计划的对该国司法机构的改革</a>。</p><p>示威者和该国的政治反对派表示，该计划将削弱以色列本已脆弱的制衡体系，并破坏民主和对少数群体的保护。他们还表示，此次改革将对以色列的民主性格造成致命打击。</p><p> <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/israels-right-wing-lawmakers-aim-to-remake-supreme-court-11668506325?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none" rel="noreferrer noopener">关于以色列最高法院的争论</a>部分是由于该国自建国以来法律体系的模糊性造成的。以色列没有成文宪法。相反，法院的判决基于英国普通法、不断发展的以色列先例和一系列基本法，这些法律提供了准宪法的权力。</p><p>围绕最高法院的斗争也成为以色列社会更深层次裂痕的代表。 <a href="https://www.wsj.com/story/why-israelis-are-protesting-netanyahu-governments-judicial-overhaul-0933acc5?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">抗议活动</a>使自由派、世俗的以色列人（他们将法院视为人权的保障者）与极端正统派以及宗教和政治保守派进行了对立，后者认为法院是实现其政策目标的障碍。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          bleed
"><figure class="media-object-image img-bleed"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="1260" height="839" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-823210?width=1260&amp;height=839" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">议会通过司法改革提案的第一部分后，耶路撒冷的抗议者。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：Orit Ben-Ezzer/Zuma Press</p></figcaption></figure></div><h3>这场危机的核心是哪些司法变革？</h3><p>内塔尼亚胡的 64 名议员组成的整个联盟于 7 月 24 日投票支持一项法律，该法律剥夺了最高法院撤销其认为“极其不合理”的政府决定的能力——他们认为这一概念含糊不清，并允许自由派法官推翻日益右翼选民的意愿。</p><p>这是联盟希望通过的一系列限制法院系统权力的法律中的第一部。接下来是一项法案，该法案将赋予立法者更多选择法官的权力，这一举措比周一通过的法案更具争议性。它可能会在秋季进行投票。</p><p> <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/netanyahu-revives-judicial-overhaul-stripped-of-most-controversial-piece-33160de" target="_blank" class="icon none" rel="noreferrer noopener">内塔尼亚胡六月告诉《华尔街日报》</a> ，他将放弃该计划在以色列以外地区最具争议的部分，这将赋予国家立法机构推翻最高法院裁决的权力。</p><p>所谓的“优先条款”将允许议会以 61 名议员的多数票否决最高法院有关立法的决定。这些提案还需要绝大多数法官才能推翻议会法律。批评者表示，拟议的改革实际上将结束对议会的司法审查，因为以色列历史上几乎每个议会联盟都拥有 61 个或更多席位。</p><h3>内塔尼亚胡为何推动司法改革计划？</h3><p>内塔尼亚胡三月份暂停了改革计划，并在大规模抗议后开始<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/israel-calms-after-netanyahu-suspends-judicial-overhaul-b951d2c?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none" rel="noreferrer noopener">与反对派进行妥协谈判</a>。但在六月下旬，他表示双方未能达成协议，他将继续推进自己修改后的计划。</p><p>这位长期执政的领导人历来都不是改革司法制度的倡导者，但他面临着来自其联盟成员的巨大压力，要求他通过这一改革。联盟成员被广泛认为是该国75年历史上最右翼、民族主义和宗教色彩最浓厚的人。</p><p>关于司法立法的辩论揭示了以色列社会对于犹太国家和民主国家的意义的分歧。该国在成立之初的几十年里是由主要是东欧血统的世俗社会主义者建立和控制的。他们设想了一个文化上犹太教但社会上自由民主的国家。</p><p>近几十年来，代表以色列右翼的不同阶层——宗教犹太复国主义者、定居者、极端正统派和中东裔犹太人——之间的联盟在数量和力量上都在增长。内塔尼亚胡领导的利库德集团本身是世俗的，它已将这些右翼势力联合成一个政治强国。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          bleed
"><figure class="media-object-image img-bleed"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="1260" height="840" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-823214?width=1260&amp;height=840" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">以色列总理本杰明·内塔尼亚胡在耶路撒冷举行的议会会议上。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：玛雅·阿莱鲁佐/美联社</p></figcaption></figure></div><h3>下一步是什么？</h3><p>最高法院现在必须决定是否接受以色列律师协会和反对派成员的请愿书，要求其废除限制其权力的法律。</p><p> 7月24日通过的立法是对以色列所谓基本法之一的修正案——零碎立法，是该国最接近宪法的立法。</p><p>以色列最高法院以前从未废除过基本法。如果法院决定听取请愿书，可能会与政府发生直接冲突。</p><p>以色列国家安全部长伊塔马尔·本-格维尔表示，最高法院否决该法案的举动将被视为“未遂政变”。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          bleed
"><figure class="media-object-image img-bleed"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="1260" height="840" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-823222?width=1260&amp;height=840" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">以色列预备役军人在特拉维夫签署一份声明。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：Matan Golan/SOPA/Zuma Press</p></figcaption></figure></div><h3>这是否会影响以色列与美国的关系？</h3><p>尽管<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/u-s-ambassador-warned-israel-against-going-off-the-rails-with-judicial-overhaul-d612fffa?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">拜登政府一再发出警告</a>，内塔尼亚胡仍继续推进司法改革，其中包括在投票前几个小时，拜登总统发表公开声明，称该措施“正在变得更加分裂，而不是减少”。</p><p>在这些措施通过后，拜登政府官员很快坚称，正如白宫新闻秘书卡琳·让-皮埃尔所说，美以关系仍然“坚如磐石”。她没有直接回答有关是否会对以色列产生切实后果的问题，并将拜登描述为以色列的终生朋友。</p><p>分析人士表示，拜登不太可能试图通过削减对以色列的援助来惩罚内塔尼亚胡，国会也可能不会支持这一举措。但以色列政府不太可能完全避免为这次投票付出代价。</p><p>华盛顿智库大西洋理事会非常驻研究员卡米尔·阿尔比特表示：“这将为国会中的人士提供素材，尤其是那些想要向拜登政府施压，要求其重新考虑两国关系的左翼人士。” “我不认为这会威胁到两国关系，但随着时间的推移，它会削弱这种关系。”</p><p><em>本说明性文章可能会定期更新。</em></p><p class="articleTagLine"> —David S. Cloud 和 Ari Flanzraich 对本文做出了贡献。</p><p>写信给 Dov Lieber，邮箱为<a href="mailto:dov.lieber@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">dov.lieber@wsj.com</a></p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Tue, 25 Jul 2023 16:08:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/israel-protests-judicial-overhaul-netanyahu-7e264a71</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/israel-protests-judicial-overhaul-netanyahu-7e264a71<author><![CDATA[Dov Lieber]]></author><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>国家/公共安全</category><category>政治/国际关系</category><category>国内政治</category><category>风险新闻</category><category>军事行动</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>伊塔玛·本·格维尔</category><category>卡琳·让·皮埃尔</category><category>卡米尔仲裁</category><category>本杰明·内塔尼亚胡</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>国家的</category><category>公安</category><category>政治</category><category>国际关系</category><category>国内政治</category><category>风险新闻</category><category>军事行动</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[July Heat Waves Nearly Impossible Without Climate Change, Study Says]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>数十年的化石燃料排放加剧了创纪录的气温<!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001082290"><div class="is-lead-inset"><div class="media-object scope-
          header
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="860" height="573" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-823199?width=860&amp;height=573" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">一项研究发现，由于化石燃料排放，本月北半球的热浪更加严重。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：理查德埃利斯/祖玛出版社</p></figcaption></figure></div></div></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001082290"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"> <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/eric-niiler" itemprop="url" rel="author">埃里克·尼尔勒</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">美国东部时间 2023 年 7 月 25 日上午 11:04 </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/july-heat-waves-nearly-impossible-without-climate-change-study-says-a6dad9e1"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><p>一组对极端天气事件进行快速评估的欧洲科学家周二发布的一项研究显示，如果没有人为引起的气候变化造成的变暖效应，本月美国、墨西哥和欧洲南部地区出现<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/extreme-heat-waves-across-the-world-photos-7cc1544d?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">极端高温</a>几乎是不可能的。</p><p>由伦敦和荷兰的研究人员组成的世界天气归因组织的研究发现，由于数十年的化石燃料排放，自 19 世纪末以来，地球平均温度升高了 2 华氏度<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/to-treat-extreme-heat-ice-packed-body-bags-and-wet-gowns-7c35c5c9?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">，因此 7 月北半球的三场独立热浪</a><a href="https://spiral.imperial.ac.uk/bitstream/10044/1/105549/8/Scientific%20Report%20-%20Northern%20Hemisphere%20Heat.pdf" target="_blank" class="icon none" rel="noopener">变得更加严重</a>。</p><p> “我们将来肯定会看到更多这样的事情，”世界天气归因联合创始人、这项新研究的作者、伦敦格兰瑟姆研究所气候科学高级讲师弗里德里克·奥托说。 “我们不知道未来的新常态或新极端是什么，因为我们不知道何时会停止燃烧化石燃料。”</p><p>该研究尚未经过同行评审，而同行评审被认为是验证研究结果的黄金标准；然而，它是基于该小组 2020 年发布的同行评审方法。</p><p>为了评估最近的热浪，科学家们运行了十几个气候模型，将本月观测到的气温与没有气​​候变暖的类似世界的预测进行了比较。他们的结论是，如果没有人类引起的气候变化，中国的极端高温将是大约250年一遇的事件，而美国、墨西哥和南欧7月的热浪几乎是不可能的。</p><p>过去几年，全球气温因太平洋三年拉尼娜天气模式的降温效应而有所缓和。现在，太平洋正在转向相反的模式，即厄尔尼诺现象，它给东太平洋带来温暖的海水，并影响全球的天气模式。</p><p>上个月是美国国家海洋和大气管理局追踪的 174 年全球气候记录中最热的 6 月。美国官员最近表示，7月第一周是自1850年有记录以来全球最热的一周，并预计整个月将是有史以来最热的一个月，超过2016年7月的上一个最热月份。</p><p>美国国家航空航天局戈达德太空研究所所长加文·施密特在上周的新闻发布会上表示：“我们预计七月可能是有记录以来最热的绝对月份，这将是一个可以追溯到数百年甚至数千年前的记录。” “我们不是每年都能看到这样的情况。”</p><p>根据美国国家海洋和大气管理局的说法，气候科学家在根据<a href="https://www.climate.gov/maps-data/climate-data-primer/past-climate" target="_blank" class="icon none">所谓的替代措施</a>进行记录之前对温度有了很好的了解，这些替代措施包括树木年轮的厚度、记录植物花粉的湖泊和海洋沉积物、从冰川和冰盖中获取的冰芯、珊瑚、化石以及来自船舶日志和早期天气观察员的记录。</p><p>研究称，7 月份的极端高温影响了美国各地 1 亿多人，墨西哥边境沿线和亚利桑那州各地已有数十人因高温死亡。研究称，墨西哥已有 200 多人因高温死亡，其中一半发生在北部新莱昂州。</p><p>菲尼克斯已连续 25 天遭受 110 度以上的高温，这是该市的最高纪录，迫使建筑工人在夜间浇筑混凝土并<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/pouring-ice-into-concrete-builders-adapt-to-extreme-heat-25142854?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">用冰桶冷却材料</a>。</p><p>写信给埃里克·尼尔勒 (Eric Niiler)： <a href="mailto:eric.niiler@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">eric.niiler@wsj.com</a></p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Tue, 25 Jul 2023 15:04:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/july-heat-waves-nearly-impossible-without-climate-change-study-says-a6dad9e1</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/july-heat-waves-nearly-impossible-without-climate-change-study-says-a6dad9e1<author><![CDATA[Eric Niiler]]></author><category>地理气候变化</category><category>华尔街日报</category><category>华尔街日报气候</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>气候变化</category><category>自然环境</category><category>全球/世界问题</category><category>科学/人文</category><category>天气</category><category>地理气候变化</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>气候变化</category><category>自然环境</category><category>全球的</category><category>世界问题</category><category>科学</category><category>人文学科</category><category>天气</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[China’s Foreign Minister Replaced After Unexplained Absence]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>习近平提拔秦刚担任外交部长几个月后被免职<!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001081700"><div class="is-lead-inset"><div class="media-object scope-
          header
"><div class="media-object-video"><div class="wsj-media-summary clearfix"><div class="strap-container"><h4 class="strap" itemprop="description"></h4></div></div><iframe width="400" height="225" src="https://video-api.wsj.com/api-video/player/v3/iframe.html?guid=9F7AF9B6-88BC-4AB6-B4C8-E0CF0C68E116&amp;height=225&amp;width=400&amp;plid=video_amp&amp;chainVideos=true&amp;parentUrl=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.wsj.com%2Famp%2Farticles%2Fchina-foreign-minister-qin-gang-replaced-63660fad&amp;a=a" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe><p class="imageCaption">北京在周二的紧急会议上重新任命最高外交官王毅接替秦刚担任外交部长，但没有提及秦刚神秘缺席的问题。照片：Florence Lo/Pool 路透社/美联社<span class="imageCredit">
        
        
        </span></p></div></div></div></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001081700"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline">作者： <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/chunhan-wong" itemprop="url" rel="author">黄春汉</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">更新于 2023 年 7 月 25 日上午 10:15（东部时间） </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/china-foreign-minister-qin-gang-replaced-63660fad"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><p>新加坡——中国领导人习近平在上任不到七个月后解除了他精心挑选的外交部长的职务，这一令人惊讶的举动给<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/china-shakes-up-government-as-xi-asserts-more-control-over-policy-ffc22275?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">中国的黑箱政治体系留下了更多的问题而不是答案。</a></p><p>秦刚在过去一个月<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/china-tries-to-reassure-u-s-amid-speculation-around-missing-foreign-minister-82697971?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none" rel="noreferrer noopener">神秘缺席</a>公共舞台后被免职，这次失踪引发了人们对他命运的猜测，并使全球关注共产党对世界第二大经济体的不透明治理。</p><p>在周二匆忙召开的会议上，中国人大常委会决定，前外交部长、现任中国最高外交官王毅将重新接任他去年年底辞去的职务。</p><p>立法者没有提供决定罢免 57 岁的秦的原因。秦接替了王，近年来在外交职务中经历了异常迅速的晋升。秦自六月下旬以来缺席重大外交活动<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/china-tries-to-reassure-u-s-amid-speculation-around-missing-foreign-minister-82697971?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none" rel="noreferrer noopener">，引发了中国国内外有关他遭遇的谣言</a>。</p><p>中国外交部此前曾以健康原因为由秦缺席本月早些时候在印度尼西亚举行的地区外交会议。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="466" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-823226?width=700&amp;height=466" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">分析人士称，王毅再次担任外交部长似乎是临时任命。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：BERNADETT SZABO/REUTERS</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>王毅现年 69 岁，是中共 24 名政治局精英成员之一，他从 2013 年初到去年 12 月担任外交部长。 10月，他作为首席外交专家加入政治局，成为中国最高外交官。</p><p>在中国的政治体系中，外交部长不一定是该国最高级别的外交官。这一角色由党内级别最高的外交政策官员担任，他是现任中共中央外事工作委员会办公室主任的王。</p><p>官方媒体报道没有提到王的党内职务有任何变化，暗示他将同时担任政治局和外交部职务——这种安排在 20 世纪 90 年代后只发生在官员过渡时期。</p><p>政治分析人士表示，王毅再次担任外交部长似乎是一项临时任命，目的是为习近平和其他高级官员制定长期安排争取时间。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="466" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-823223?width=700&amp;height=466" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">秦刚今年早些时候在开罗工作。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：Amr Nabil/美联社</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>华盛顿战略与国际研究中心的中国问题分析师裘德·布兰切特表示：“秦的免职不应被解读为习近平权力的削弱，习近平权力的范围比任何一项任命都要广泛和深入。” “事实上，目前秦保留了一些党内和政府职位，这表明存在一些尚未解决的内部问题。”</p><p>官方媒体在周二的全国人民代表大会常务委员会会议上没有提到秦国务委员的角色有任何变化，国务委员是中国国务院的高级政府级别。截至周二晚间，国务院网站仍将秦列为国务委员。</p><p>党当局尚未宣布秦作为205名党中央委员之一的地位有任何变化，他于10月加入中国驻美国大使。</p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          wrap
"></div><p>周二的立法会议是提前一天安排的，通知时间异常短，并且超出了常务委员会例行会议的典型两个月周期。这次特别会议是在周一由习近平主持的政治局会议之后召开的。</p><p> “总体外交政策不太可能在秦被赶下台后发生变化，因为他的作用只是执行习近平做出的关键决策，”布兰切特说。</p><p>秦的谜团引发了人们对习近平领导下的中国治理的新质疑，习近平的共产党加倍强调保密性， <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/china-locks-information-on-the-country-inside-a-black-box-9c039928" target="_blank" class="icon none" rel="noreferrer noopener">挫败了外界获取有关这个领先经济强国发展信息的努力</a>。</p><p>秦被认为<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/china-promotes-u-s-ambassador-to-foreign-minister-11672409545?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none" rel="noreferrer noopener">是习近平值得信赖的助手</a>，在担任中国领导人的礼宾司司长后，近年来在中国外交部门中获得了异常迅速的晋升。尽管秦没有直接处理美国关系的正式背景，但他于 2021 年被任命为北京驻华盛顿大使，随后加入中央委员会并于去年底晋升为外交部长，这打破了传统上除了政治关系之外还重视经验的体制中的先例。</p><p>政治分析人士表示，秦与习近平的密切关系使他的缺席显得特别耐人寻味。由于缺乏有关秦行踪的信息，社交媒体上引发了各种猜测，其中包括围绕其婚外情可能性的猜测。</p><p>中国外交部于7月11日首次就秦失踪事件发表评论，当时在例行新闻发布会上表示，秦因健康原因不会出席在雅加达举行的国际外长会议，但没有透露任何细节。此后，外交部发言人普遍回避有关秦的问题。</p><p>在中国不透明的政治体系中，健康问题经常被认为是高级官员缺席的原因。党内人士表示，虽然这种解释往往是真实的，但有时它可能成为政治问题的掩护。</p><p> 2012年2月，当内陆大城市重庆市公安局前局长王立军失踪时，市政府称他正在接受“度假式治疗”，以缓解压力和过度劳累，但实际上他已经逃到附近城市成都的美国领事馆<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB10000872396390444100404577643450001423304" target="_blank" class="icon none">寻求庇护</a>。</p><p>新加坡李光耀公共政策学院副教授吴阿尔弗雷德·吴(Alfred Wu)表示，北京方面取代秦出任外交部长的举动不会平息对其命运的猜测，因为这留下了许多关于他长期缺席的原因的疑问。</p><p>在周二的全国人大会议上，立法者还任命潘功胜为中国人民银行行长。自2012年以来一直担任副行长的60岁的潘本月早些时候被<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/china-plans-to-appoint-a-new-central-bank-governor-56a878ea" target="_blank" class="icon none" rel="noreferrer noopener">任命为央行党内最高官员后，</a>此举就在预料之中。</p><p>据《华尔街日报》报道，在习近平任命他领导央行之前的几周内，这位资深经济学家和银行家一直在<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/the-man-charged-with-steering-the-yuan-through-chinas-economic-turmoil-37574af8" target="_blank" class="icon none" rel="noreferrer noopener">准备退休</a>，当时人民币一直在贬值。</p><p>写信给 Chun Han Wong： <a href="mailto:chunhan.wong@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">chunhan.wong@wsj.com</a></p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Tue, 25 Jul 2023 14:15:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/china-foreign-minister-qin-gang-replaced-63660fad</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/china-foreign-minister-qin-gang-replaced-63660fad<author><![CDATA[Chun Han Wong]]></author><category>经济新闻</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>国际关系</category><category>政治/国际关系</category><category>国内政治</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>经济新闻</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>国际关系</category><category>政治</category><category>国内政治</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[Israel Faces New Security Threats if Protesting Military Reservists Refuse to Serve]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>该国面临来自伊朗支持的真主党的越来越大的风险，同时与华盛顿的关系紧张<!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001081692"><div class="is-lead-inset"><div class="media-object scope-
          header
"><div class="media-object-video"><div class="wsj-media-summary clearfix"><div class="strap-container"><h4 class="strap" itemprop="description"></h4></div></div><iframe width="400" height="225" src="https://video-api.wsj.com/api-video/player/v3/iframe.html?guid=B58B7540-4CF9-464C-A04F-C0E71926FD01&amp;height=225&amp;width=400&amp;plid=video_amp&amp;chainVideos=true&amp;parentUrl=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.wsj.com%2Famp%2Farticles%2Fisraels-judicial-overhaul-raises-security-concerns-as-reservists-refuse-to-serve-5d68bfff&amp;a=a" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe><p class="imageCaption">以色列医生周二举行罢工，当局在因总理本杰明·内塔尼亚胡政府进行的司法改革而发生骚乱的夜晚，强行将抗议者从道路上带走。照片：阿米尔·利维/盖蒂图片社<span class="imageCredit">
        
        
        </span></p></div></div></div></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001081692"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline">作者： <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/david-s-cloud" itemprop="url" rel="author">大卫·S·克劳德</a></span>和<span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/dov-lieber" itemprop="url" rel="author">多夫·利伯</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">美国东部时间 2023 年 7 月 25 日上午 8:33 </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/israels-judicial-overhaul-raises-security-concerns-as-reservists-refuse-to-serve-5d68bfff"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><p>数月来，围绕总理本雅明·内塔尼亚胡在议会推动的司法改革引发的<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/israeli-doctors-go-on-strike-to-protest-netanyahus-judicial-overhaul-463530e7?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">内部动荡</a>，使以色列面临着充满挑战的安全环境，其军事准备情况受到质疑，伊朗支持的真主党激进组织对以色列北部边境的威胁日益加大，与其最大盟友华盛顿的<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/biden-netanyahu-agree-to-meet-later-this-year-247c33f7?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">关系也紧张</a>。</p><p>黎巴嫩政治和激进组织真主党领导人哈桑·纳斯鲁拉表示，周一“正如一些人所说，是犹太复国主义实体历史上最糟糕的一天”，该国是一个“地区大国，其信仰、意识和自信已经开始恶化，陷入今天所经历的危机”。</p><p>周一通过的<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/israel-netanyahu-government-judicial-overhaul-protests-862dffd3?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">限制该国最高法院权力的立法</a>已经不再是一个国内政治问题，此前数千名预备役军人威胁拒绝报到以示抗议，这对高度依赖具有多年战斗机飞行员、情报分析员和特种作战部队持续行动经验的志愿者的军队来说是一个潜在的破坏性打击。</p><p>尽管有多少人会兑现这一承诺还有待观察，但一名以色列军方官员周一表示，数量有限的预备役军人已经停止参加训练。他们的决定的影响可能要几个月才能感受到，但高级军事官员警告内塔尼亚胡， <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/israel-protests-judicial-overhaul-netanyahu-7e264a71?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">该立法正在损害</a>军队队伍的团结，并可能影响其长期战斗准备。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="466" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-823125?width=700&amp;height=466" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">耶路撒冷民众周一举行游行，抗议司法改革。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：阿米尔·利维/盖蒂图片社</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>一些预备役军人可能会在未来几天或几周内通知他们的指挥官，他们不会去上班。以色列预备役军人全年定期服役，从每周一天到每年一整月不等。</p><p>内塔尼亚胡在周一晚上的讲话中呼吁抗议者让该国军队远离“任何政治争议”。</p><p> “我们都知道，以色列国防军依赖热爱这个国家的敬业预备役军人，”他指的是以色列国防军。 “拒绝服务的呼吁损害了该州每个公民的安全。”</p><p>预备役军人表示，他们并不是反对某种政治立场，而是反对他们认为会破坏民主的立法。</p><p>以色列国防军拥有 169,000 名现役军人和 465,000 名预备役军人，仍然是中东地区最强大的部队，其部分最先进的无人机和其他武器来自以色列技术部门和美国，美国每年向以色列提供 38 亿美元的军事援助。</p><p>如果从事需要高度发展技能的军事工作的预备役人员停止志愿执行任务和训练，以色列国防军仍然有能力应对大多数威胁。分析人士表示，在安全危机中，许多承诺退出的预备役军人可能会重返岗位。分析师表示，真正的影响可能是更长期的。</p><p>美国犹太人组织以色列政策论坛首席政策官迈克尔·科普洛表示：“以色列国防军依赖这样一个事实，即以色列是一个小国，除了极端正统犹太人之外的每个人都同意服役。” “一旦这个问题被打破，我认为修复起来将非常困难。”</p><p>以色列议会周一批准的这项措施旨在限制以色列最高法院使用被称为“合理性”的法律标准，该法院过去曾通过声称政府或行政部门的决定“极其不合理”来推翻这些决定。支持者表示，该原则允许法院出于政治目的推翻民选官员的意愿。</p><p>周六，包括前军方、摩萨德外国间谍机构和辛贝特国内安全机构负责人在内的数十名前高级安全官员写信给内塔尼亚胡，支持预备役抗议，并警告总理，他的政策正在侵蚀维持以色列等“人民军队”模式所需的社会凝聚力。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="466" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-823127?width=700&amp;height=466" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">以色列总理本杰明·内塔尼亚胡出席限制最高法院权力法案的投票。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：阿米尔·科恩/路透社</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>司法改革引起了以色列社会某些方面的强烈反对，他们声称这些变化旨在阻止最高法院阻止内塔尼亚胡的极右翼联盟伙伴推行有争议的立法，这些立法可能包括吞并被占领的约旦河西岸部分地区，声称犹太人在耶路撒冷有争议的圣地有更强大的存在，或者在约旦河西岸大幅扩大以色列定居点。</p><p>其中许多目标与美国长期以来的中东政策相矛盾，美国支持与以色列一起建立一个独立的巴勒斯坦国。</p><p>尽管拜登政府一再发出警告，内塔尼亚胡仍继续推进司法改革，其中包括在投票前几小时发出的周日警告，当时拜登总统发表公开声明，称该措施“变得更加分裂，而不是减少”。</p><p>正如白宫新闻秘书卡琳·让-皮埃尔所说，拜登政府官员在这些措施通过后很快坚称，美以关系仍然“坚如磐石”</p>把它。她没有直接回答有关是否会对以色列产生切实后果的问题，并将拜登描述为以色列的终生朋友。 <p></p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="466" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-823133?width=700&amp;height=466" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">真主党战士在黎巴嫩阿拉姆塔参加军事演习。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：anwar amro/法新社/盖蒂图片社</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>分析人士表示，拜登不太可能试图通过削减对以色列的援助来惩罚内塔尼亚胡，国会也可能不会支持这一举措。但以色列政府不太可能完全避免为这次投票付出代价。</p><p>华盛顿智库大西洋理事会非常驻研究员卡米尔·阿尔比特表示：“这将为国会中的人士提供素材，尤其是那些想要向拜登政府施压，要求其重新考虑两国关系的左翼人士。” “我不认为这会威胁到两国关系，但随着时间的推移，它会削弱这种关系。”</p><p>华盛顿和其他担心以色列走向的盟友以及渴望利用任何软弱迹象的中东对手都在密切关注司法改革。随着以色列在中东的地缘政治地位今年受到侵蚀，围绕司法改革的争论正在发生。内塔尼亚胡曾抱有与沙特阿拉伯实现关系正常化的希望，但利雅得却<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/saudi-arabia-iran-restore-relations-in-deal-brokered-by-china-406393a1?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">与伊朗重新建立了外交关系</a>，伊朗加大了对真主党和其他<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/iran-is-recruiting-militant-allies-to-launch-attacks-against-israel-c40f369f?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">反以色列代理人</a>的支持。</p><p>据以色列安全官员称，真主党在以色列北部边境地区的侵略行为尤其严重。他们说，真主党正在边境关键地点悄悄集结部队，纯白色的拖车上挂着天线。这些地点距离边境如此之近，黎巴嫩方面的男子经常向以色列士兵投掷石块。他们还切断了边境的安全围栏，导致士兵们仓皇失措。以色列官员表示，这些地点都有穿着便衣和作战服的人员在操作。</p><p>以色列官员表示，真主党特工从未如此公开地行动过。 “他们不再伪装了，”一名以色列军方官员说。 “这是一个新现象。” </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="466" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-823129?width=700&amp;height=466" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">阿克萨烈士旅的巴勒斯坦枪手出现在约旦河西岸的巴拉塔难民营中。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：Nasser Ishtayeh/Zuma Press</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>除了真主党最近采取的其他行动外，以色列官员表示，这是自 2006 年双方进行了为期 34 天的战争以来，伊朗支持的组织采取的最公开的侵略行动，这场战争导致 165 名以色列人和 1,100 名黎巴嫩人死亡。</p><p>司法改革引发的数月动乱也恰逢与约旦河西岸巴勒斯坦武装分子发生致命冲突。以色列军队频繁袭击巴勒斯坦城市和难民营，与装备精良的武装分子发生<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/israel-raids-west-bank-with-armored-vehicles-and-drones-killing-at-least-eight-17e0c7c8?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">血腥对抗</a>。上个月，在约旦河西岸的一场枪战中，以色列军用直升机向巴勒斯坦武装分子开火，这是多年来的首次枪战升级。</p><p>分析人士和以色列安全官员表示，真主党变得更加大胆，部分原因是伊朗和真主党认为以色列由于长期的政治动荡而内部软弱。伊朗可能仍会犹豫是否尝试用自杀式无人机或其他武器直接打击以色列，但它可能会释放其代理人力量。</p><div class="media-object scope-web
          wrap
"><div class="media-object-rich-text"><h4>分享你的意见</h4><p><em>您认为内塔尼亚胡总理试图改革司法系统会产生什么连锁反应？加入下面的对话。</em></p></div></div><p>以色列军方官员称，真主党拥有超过 10 万枚火箭弹，瞄准以色列，其中大部分隐藏在黎巴嫩南部周围的住宅和其他民用场所。以色列官员称，真主党还生产了数百枚精确制导导弹，可以打击以色列任何地方，例如敏感燃料设施或军事场所。</p><p>真主党近年来发布了许多视频，旨在向以色列展示其导弹武器库可以造成多大的破坏。</p><p> “我们看到，随着这些抗议活动的进行，真主党一直在考验以色列，”负责中东事务的前国务院官员、现任华盛顿政策组织华盛顿近东政策研究所研究员的戴维·申克(David Schenker)说。 “由于以色列在叙利亚追击伊朗这么久，我认为对德黑兰来说仍然有足够的威慑力，但代理人不受相同游戏规则的约束。”</p><p>写信给 David S. Cloud <a href="mailto:david.cloud@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">（david.cloud@wsj.com）</a>和 Dov Lieber（ <a href="mailto:dov.lieber@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">dov.lieber@wsj.com</a> ）</p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Tue, 25 Jul 2023 12:33:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/israels-judicial-overhaul-raises-security-concerns-as-reservists-refuse-to-serve-5d68bfff</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/israels-judicial-overhaul-raises-security-concerns-as-reservists-refuse-to-serve-5d68bfff<author><![CDATA[David S. CloudDov Lieber]]></author><category>华尔街日报</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>内乱</category><category>国家/公共安全</category><category>社会/社区</category><category>犯罪/法律诉讼</category><category>武装部队</category><category>国际关系</category><category>政治/国际关系</category><category>国内政治</category><category>风险新闻</category><category>社会问题</category><category>间谍</category><category>恐怖主义</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法激活过滤器</category><category>C&amp;E 行政新闻过滤器</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>本杰明·内塔尼亚胡</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>内乱</category><category>国家的</category><category>公安</category><category>社会</category><category>社区</category><category>犯罪</category><category>合法举动</category><category>武装部队</category><category>国际关系</category><category>政治</category><category>国内政治</category><category>风险新闻</category><category>社会问题</category><category>间谍</category><category>恐怖主义</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法蒂瓦过滤器</category><category>C&amp;E 行政新闻过滤器</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[Israeli Doctors Go On Strike Over Netanyahu’s Judicial Overhaul]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>政治反对派以色列律师协会请愿最高法院否决新法律<!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001081582"><div class="is-lead-inset"><div class="media-object scope-
          header
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="860" height="573" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-823093?width=860&amp;height=573" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">耶路撒冷警方对抗议者使用高压水枪。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：阿米尔·利维/盖蒂图片社</p></figcaption></figure></div></div></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001081582"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"> <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/dov-lieber" itemprop="url" rel="author">多夫·利伯</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">美国东部时间 2023 年 7 月 25 日上午 6:20 </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/israeli-doctors-go-on-strike-to-protest-netanyahus-judicial-overhaul-463530e7"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><p>特拉维夫——周二，以色列的医生和医务人员举行罢工，抗议本杰明·内塔尼亚胡总理政府正在进行的<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/israel-netanyahu-government-judicial-overhaul-protests-862dffd3?mod=hp_lead_pos7&amp;mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none" rel="noreferrer noopener">司法改革中第一项法案的通过</a>。</p><p>尽管抗议数月，该法案还是由执政联盟推动通过，引发了大规模的反对政府示威活动。 The police said late Monday that 15 protesters were arrested for rioting and attacking police, with authorities forcibly removing some demonstrators blocking streets in Tel Aviv. Police used water cannons to disperse protesters in Tel Aviv, police footage showed.</p><p> On Tuesday, besides the strike called by the medical workers, it wasn&#39;t clear if there were any other major demonstrations planned. Protests have often been spontaneous and usually in the evenings.</p><p> Israel&#39;s largest labor union, Histadrut, said Monday it was preparing for the possibility of calling a general strike, and some protesters were pressing it to make such a move. However, the union decided against declaring a general strike for now.</p><p> The Supreme Court will now have to decide whether to accept the petitions it has received from the Israel Bar Association and members of the opposition asking for it to strike down the law that limits its own powers. </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><div class="media-object-video"><div class="wsj-media-summary clearfix"><div class="strap-container"><h4 class="strap" itemprop="description"></h4></div></div><iframe width="400" height="225" src="https://video-api.wsj.com/api-video/player/v3/iframe.html?guid=E3E72531-794A-477C-836E-5960EF41E94A&amp;height=225&amp;width=400&amp;plid=video_amp&amp;chainVideos=true&amp;parentUrl=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.wsj.com%2Famp%2Farticles%2Fisraeli-doctors-go-on-strike-to-protest-netanyahus-judicial-overhaul-463530e7&amp;a=a" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe><p class="imageCaption"> Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu&#39;s coalition on Monday passed the first bill in a contentious judicial overhaul that seeks to limit the power of the Supreme Court. WSJ&#39;s Dov Lieber reports from Jerusalem. Photo: Corinna Kern/Reuters<span class="imageCredit">
        
        
        </span></p></div></div><p>The bill that passed Monday takes away the court&#39;s ability to nullify government decisions it finds “unreasonable in the extreme,” a standard that is used by the court to ensure government decisions are taken with appropriate considerations. This includes the hiring and firing of key government appointments such as government ministers, the attorney general and heads of the security services.</p><p> The Israeli Medical Association said it called the strike because the new law removes judicial scrutiny over the political leadership of the health ministry, which it said would have “serious consequences for the health system, patients and doctors.” The association said it had lobbied the government to keep that judicial scrutiny in place over the health system.</p><p> The legislation that was passed on Monday was an amendment to one of Israel&#39;s so-called basic laws—piecemeal legislation that is the closest thing the country has to a constitution.</p><p> Israel&#39;s Supreme Court has never struck down a basic law before. If the court decides to hear the petitions, it could put it in direct conflict with the government.</p><p> Israel&#39;s National Security Minister Itamar Ben-Gvir</p> said a move by the top court to strike the bill down would be seen as “an attempted coup.”<p></p><p> It is the first in a series of laws the coalition government wants to pass to limit the power of the court system. Next up is a bill that would give lawmakers more power to select judges—a move that is more contentious than the bill passed on Monday. It could be voted on in the fall.</p><p> The law&#39;s passage marks a pivotal juncture for Israeli society. It presents a decisive moment for thousands of military reservists, who have said they would quit, while business and union leaders have also threatened mass work stoppages.</p><p>写信给 Dov Lieber，邮箱为<a href="mailto:dov.lieber@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">dov.lieber@wsj.com</a></p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Tue, 25 Jul 2023 10:20:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/israeli-doctors-go-on-strike-to-protest-netanyahus-judicial-overhaul-463530e7</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/israeli-doctors-go-on-strike-to-protest-netanyahus-judicial-overhaul-463530e7<author><![CDATA[Dov Lieber]]></author><category> israel</category><category> Labor/Personnel</category><category>企业/行业新闻</category><category>Labor Disputes</category><category>突击</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>Civil Unrest</category><category>国家/公共安全</category><category>社会/社区</category><category>犯罪/法律诉讼</category><category>一般劳工问题</category><category>政治/国际关系</category><category>国内政治</category><category>Risk News</category><category>国家安全措施/政策</category><category>社会问题</category><category>Military Action</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法激活过滤器</category><category>会展行业新闻过滤器</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>本杰明·内塔尼亚胡</category><category>labor</category><category>人员</category><category>公司的</category><category>行业新闻</category><category>labor disputes</category><category>突击</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>civil unrest</category><category>国家的</category><category>公安</category><category>社会</category><category>社区</category><category>犯罪</category><category>合法举动</category><category>一般劳工问题</category><category>政治</category><category>国际关系</category><category>国内政治</category><category>risk news</category><category>国家安全措施</category><category>政策</category><category>社会问题</category><category>military action</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法蒂瓦过滤器</category><category>会展行业新闻过滤器</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[The World Tied $3.5 Trillion-Plus of Debt to Inflation. The Costs Are Now Adding Up.]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div> With roughly $770 billion of borrowings linked to retail prices, Britain is feeling the pinch <figure><img src="https://images.wsj.net/im-822961/?width=1278&amp;size=1" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><figcaption> Alexandra Citrin-Safadi/The Wall Street Journal; Photo: iStock <span>Alexandra Citrin-Safadi/The Wall Street Journal; Photo: iStock</span> </figcaption></figure><!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001080744"></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001080744"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"> By <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/chelsey-dulaney" itemprop="url" rel="author">Chelsey Dulaney</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1"> July 25, 2023 5:59 am ET </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/the-world-tied-3-5-trillion-plus-of-debt-to-inflation-the-costs-are-now-adding-up-b8db69d5"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          bigtophero
"></div><p> Governments and companies around the world spent decades loading up on trillions of dollars of debt whose interest costs rise and fall alongside inflation. But what served as cheap funding when prices were stagnant has rapidly become more expensive.</p><p> The inflation-linked headache echoes the broader challenges arising at the end of more than a decade of global easy money, in which debtors borrowed vast amounts at very low, and sometimes negative, interest rates. Investors are on alert for financial vulnerabilities after a <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/the-banking-sector-turmoil-in-charts-52bb6095?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">crisis in US regional banks</a> this year, and with <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/hedge-funds-brawl-over-battered-commercial-real-estate-1a12df4?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">strains emerging</a> in commercial property.</p><p> Borrowing costs of all sorts have risen sharply for governments, businesses and consumers, as central banks have raised key interest rates to combat price pressures. Rates have surged on inflation-linked borrowings, but these aren&#39;t the only source of pain.</p><p> As standard bonds with fixed rates mature, they need to be replaced with more expensive new debt. Meanwhile, interest rates on loans are often floating, meaning they quickly reflect changes in policy rates.</p><p> Yields on benchmark 10-year fixed-rate bonds, a proxy for government borrowing costs, have climbed to about 4.3% for the UK and 3.9% for the US Both were below 1% during the pandemic.</p><p> Governments will pay roughly $2.2 trillion in overall debt interest this year, Fitch Ratings estimates. The US Treasury&#39;s <a href="https://fiscaldata.treasury.gov/datasets/monthly-treasury-statement/summary-of-receipts-outlays-and-the-deficit-surplus-of-the-u-s-government" target="_blank" class="icon none" rel="noopener">interest cost grew 25%</a> to $652 billion in the nine months through June. Germany&#39;s debt-servicing bill <a href="https://dserver.bundestag.de/btd/20/031/2003101.pdf" target="_blank" class="icon none">is expected to soar</a> to 30 billion euros this year, or some $33.2 billion, from €4 billion in 2021.</p><p> Governments had $3.5 trillion in outstanding inflation-linked debt at the end of 2022, according to the Bank for International Settlements, equivalent to about 11% of their total borrowings.</p><p> The poster child for the inflation-linked problem is Britain, which has experienced the fastest rise in debt costs in the Group of Seven advanced democracies. The UK first embraced such debt under Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher and in 1981 became one of the first developed economies to issue inflation-linked debt: securities that are known as linkers there and Treasury Inflation-Protected Securities, or TIPS, in the US Both the amount due to investors once the bonds mature and the regular interest payments they receive move with inflation.</p><p> About a quarter of UK debt is now tied to inflation, trailing only a handful of emerging markets with a history of runaway prices such as Uruguay, Brazil and Chile. </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          inline
"><img width="600" height="800" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-823083?width=600" alt="不明确的" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><p> “We stick out like a sore thumb,” said Sanjay Raja, chief UK economist at Deutsche Bank.</p><p> The UK&#39;s debt woes are complicated by its longstanding reliance on a measure of price increases that has fallen out of favor: the retail price index, or RPI. Some 600 billion pounds, equivalent to roughly $770 billion, of bonds are linked to this gauge, which has consistently risen faster than more widely used consumer-price indexes. London has pledged to phase out RPI by 2030.</p><p> Inflation as measured by the RPI topped 14% in October and was still 11% in June compared with a year earlier. Economists expect UK inflation to keep falling this year, albeit <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/u-k-s-stubborn-inflation-means-more-pain-for-homeowners-renters-94f44e96?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">more slowly than in other major economies</a> . </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          wrap
"><img width="600" height="800" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-823100?width=600" alt="不明确的" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><p> In theory, higher interest payouts should be balanced by rising revenue. While higher inflation means bigger payouts to bondholders, it should also bring in more taxes.</p><p> That logic holds especially true in markets like the UK, where inflation gauges are deeply embedded in the economy. Tax thresholds, pension and welfare payments, rail fares and cellphone bills are often linked to price indexes.</p><p> But the energy shock that fueled recent inflation upended that math, since higher energy bills drove up RPI even as earnings and consumer spending lagged behind. The UK is experiencing the “wrong sort of inflation,” the UK&#39;s Office for Budget Responsibility said this month. The sensitivity of UK debt to inflation was unprecedented, the watchdog said. </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          inline
"><img width="600" height="800" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-823101?width=600" alt="不明确的" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><p> The UK&#39;s debt sustainability is a focus for investors after <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/u-k-markets-rally-as-investors-bet-government-will-roll-back-tax-plans-11665671654?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">a market meltdown</a> last fall, triggered by then-Prime Minister Liz Truss&#39;s tax-cutting plans.</p><p> Her successor Rishi Sunak and his Chancellor</p> Jeremy Hunt have sought to restore market confidence with pledges to contain inflation and bring down debt. As the UK&#39;s interest costs climb, and with debt now surpassing 100% of gross domestic product, those promises are getting harder to keep while maintaining investor confidence.<p></p><p> The debt burden also undermines Sunak&#39;s hopes to woo voters and revive the economy with tax cuts and spending measures ahead of a general election expected to take place next year.</p><p> “We could quickly be in a situation where we&#39;re facing some renewed sense of crisis, particularly with an economic backdrop of stagflation with really weak growth and overshooting inflation,” said Mark Dowding, chief investment officer at RBC BlueBay Asset Management in London. “Further policy missteps could easily be punished by the market.”</p><p> Higher bond yields and stickier inflation will add an extra £30 billion to the UK&#39;s annual government debt bill, estimates Bank of America economist Robert Wood. </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><div class="media-object-video"><div class="wsj-media-summary clearfix"><div class="strap-container"><h4 class="strap" itemprop="description"></h4></div></div><iframe width="400" height="225" src="https://video-api.wsj.com/api-video/player/v3/iframe.html?guid=8721652E-C4D0-4BCA-A94F-5BE086258F7E&amp;height=225&amp;width=400&amp;plid=video_amp&amp;chainVideos=true&amp;parentUrl=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.wsj.com%2Famp%2Farticles%2Fthe-world-tied-3-5-trillion-plus-of-debt-to-inflation-the-costs-are-now-adding-up-b8db69d5&amp;a=a" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe><p class="imageCaption"> Core inflation is rising in the UK while falling in other big economies like the US WSJ&#39;s Anna Hirtenstein explains why, and how it affects Prime Minister Rishi Sunak&#39;s goal of halving inflation by the end of 2023. Illustration: Daniel Orton/WSJ<span class="imageCredit">
        
        
        </span></p></div></div><p>“The government has three options: You can plan for weaker spending, you could raise taxes or you could borrow more,” he said. “Certainly one could say that this rise in debt-interest costs is incompatible with cutting taxes.”</p><p> The UK is selling fewer linkers, which are likely to make up 11% of bond issuance this fiscal year, down from above 20% throughout the 2010s.</p><p> One veteran UK central banker said linkers had largely done their job as envisioned in the 1980s.</p><p> “We were coming out of a decade in which inflation had been extremely high. People were very skeptical about the ability of any government, particularly the Conservative government, to bring inflation down to a low and stable rate,” said Charles Goodhart, who was an adviser at the Bank of England between 1969 and 1985.</p><p> Fears that linkers would lead to fresh wage-price spirals as unions demanded <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/u-k-faces-new-wave-of-strikes-as-workers-fight-for-higher-pay-11672755114?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">inflation-linked increases</a> , didn&#39;t play out, he said. Thatcher, who called inflation “the destroyer of all,” saw linkers as “sleeping policemen,” ensuring the government wasn&#39;t tempted to let inflation run to help inflate debt away.</p><div class="media-object scope-web
          wrap
"><div class="media-object-rich-text"><h4> SHARE YOUR THOUGHTS</h4><p> <em>How can the UK government address its rising debt obligations? Join the conversation below.</em></p></div></div><p> “It makes the current fiscal position more difficult. But that&#39;s what Mrs. Thatcher actually wanted,” said Goodhart. “She wanted governments to resist inflation more strongly.”</p><p> Companies are also feeling the pressure from inflation-linked borrowing. The UK&#39;s largest water company, Thames Water, nearly collapsed in recent weeks as investors questioned its ability to repay £14 billion in debt, about half of which is linked to inflation. Thames Water&#39;s debt is RPI-linked, but customer prices now track CPI, which lags behind the RPI by about 3 percentage points more slowly.</p><p> Write to Chelsey Dulaney at <a href="mailto:chelsey.dulaney@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">chelsey.dulaney@wsj.com</a></p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Tue, 25 Jul 2023 09:59:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/the-world-tied-3-5-trillion-plus-of-debt-to-inflation-the-costs-are-now-adding-up-b8db69d5</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/the-world-tied-3-5-trillion-plus-of-debt-to-inflation-the-costs-are-now-adding-up-b8db69d5<author><![CDATA[Chelsey Dulaney]]></author><category>企业/行业新闻</category><category>政府财政</category><category>Government Borrowing</category><category>经济新闻</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>公司的</category><category>行业新闻</category><category>政府财政</category><category>government borrowing</category><category>经济新闻</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[A Soap Maker Cracks the Code to ‘Made in America’]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div> Bath &amp; Body Works persuaded suppliers to set up production in an Ohio city near its headquarters <figure><img src="https://images.wsj.net/im-822326/?width=1278&amp;size=1" alt="Label  manufacturer CCL is one of the suppliers for Bath &amp; Body Works in New Albany, Ohio." referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><figcaption> Label manufacturer CCL is one of the suppliers for Bath &amp; Body Works in New Albany, Ohio. <span></span></figcaption></figure><!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001075938"></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001075938"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"> By <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/austen-hufford" itemprop="url" rel="author">Austen Hufford</a></span> / Photographs by Maddie McGarvey for The Wall Street Journal</div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1"> July 25, 2023 5:30 am ET </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/bath-body-works-us-manufacturing-413cf9d0"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          bigtophero
"></div><p> NEW ALBANY, Ohio—A $7.95 bottle of <a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/BBWI" class="company-name">Bath &amp; Body Works</a> foaming hand soap used to take three months to put together. The pieces had to travel more than 13,000 miles from China, Canada and Virginia to the company&#39;s Ohio distribution center.</p><p> Bath &amp; Body Works decided it needed to get new products to market more quickly. The result was a <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/u-s-companies-on-pace-to-bring-home-record-number-of-overseas-jobs-11660968061?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">production</a> initiative with little parallel in corporate America.</p><p> Now every step of production occurs at plants just feet from each other on the company&#39;s dedicated “beauty park” on the outskirts of Columbus. One factory makes the foaming pump and mechanism. Another makes the bottle itself, a third makes the label, a fourth makes the soap, fills the bottle, attaches the label and screws on the top. A fifth packages it. Getting a bottle to distribution is down to 21 days and a few miles. A majority of Bath &amp; Body Works products, which are sold in its own stores, are made on site.</p><p> The effort, which started in 2008, required a lot of negotiation with sometimes skeptical suppliers. The campus includes 10 manufacturers and millions of square feet of production and warehouse spaces, with 5,000 employees working there during peak production. Bath &amp; Body Works had sales of $7.56 billion last year, increasing annual revenue by more than $2 billion since 2019.</p><p> “I look at BBW as a composer and a conductor of a symphony,” said Bath &amp; Body Works supply-chain executive Susanna Zhu.</p><p> Bringing production closer to home has become a priority for many companies. Disruptions from Covid-19, severe weather, trade wars, geopolitical tensions and stuck ships left consumers without the couches and <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/why-is-the-supply-chain-still-so-snarled-we-explain-with-a-hot-tub-11629987531?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">hot tubs</a> they wanted. The Biden administration is spending hundreds of billions of dollars aimed at boosting the domestic presence of industries deemed strategic, including electric cars, batteries and semiconductors.</p><p> The government money, along with roaring consumer demand and persistent supply-chain issues, are leading to a <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/american-manufacturing-factory-jobs-comeback-3ce0c52c?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">factory building boom</a> , with spending at its highest level in at least 20 years. Over the next decade, public and private investment will amount to $3.5 trillion, the government estimates.</p><p> Bath &amp; Body Works&#39; initiative proved particularly helpful during the pandemic. While competitors struggled with shortages, BBW&#39;s suppliers on location shared raw materials and even employees to make more hand sanitizer and other in-demand goods. </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="466" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-822324?width=700&amp;height=466" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Daniel Rice, a press operator at CCL, works the line.</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> Chief Executive Gina Boswell</p> said locating corporate executives just a short drive away from key manufacturers allows problems to be fixed and new products developed quickly.<p></p><p> “That&#39;s magical, especially when you need speed and agility,” she said.</p><p> The company, which like many retailers benefited from increased consumer spending in the pandemic, said <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/bath-body-works-financial-chief-wendy-arlin-to-leave-e6b40c91?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">sales could fall</a> this year.</p><p> One <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/craftsman-america-wrench-stanley-black-decker-reshoring-factory-1125792f?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">challenge</a> to replicating BBW&#39;s model is that factories don&#39;t operate in bubbles, but rely on networks of suppliers, parts and expertise—and moving those networks is costly. Once such a network has been established, it tends to get stuck there.</p><p> Land, labor and compliance with environmental and zoning laws also generally cost more in the US than in China and developing countries.</p><p> What works for soap and the two dozen other products BBW makes won&#39;t necessarily translate to smartphones, blenders or even backpacks with highly specialized supply chains deeply rooted in Asia. </p><div class="media-object scope-
          bleed
"><figure class="media-object-image img-bleed"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="1260" height="840" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-822322?width=1260&amp;height=840" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Hari Poudel packages Bath &amp; Body Works soap at KDC/One, another supplier in New Albany.</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> Semiconductor manufacturers and raw steel producers require massive upfront investment and economies of scale. The BBW model is better suited to exploiting economies of scope, in which a manufacturer produces a variety of products. Bath &amp; Body Works can roll out around 7,000 new scented products a year.</p><p> BBW, whose headquarters is about 10 miles from the beauty park, was founded by <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/leslie-wexner-to-leave-board-of-l-brands-11616072589?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">Les Wexner</a> as part of his retail conglomerate, L Brands. The body-products seller grew from 27 stores in 1990 to more than 1,000 in 1999 and 1,810 as of April. In 2021 L Brands spun off its</p> <a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/VSCO" class="company-name">Victoria&#39;s Secret</a> lingerie stores and changed its name to Bath &amp; Body Works, focusing exclusively on that brand.<p></p><p> For its beauty campus, the company chose New Albany, a planned community close to a major highway and a day&#39;s drive from nearly half the country&#39;s population.</p><p> New Albany wanted to diversify its white-collar economy. To entice BBW, the city created zoning and installed infrastructure at a cost of $6 million to itself and $3 million from the state. The early factories opened on the 450-acre site in 2011. </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          edgetoedge
"><iframe width="300" height="300" src="https://graphics.wsj.com/dynamic-inset-iframer/?url=https://asset.wsj.net/wsjnewsgraphics/projects/narrator/818b84a5-1525-40bd-9eac-752c4fe195f1.json" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe></div><p> To make it happen, BBW had to persuade its best suppliers to move. The plus for suppliers was continuing to do business with a fast-growing skin-care seller—with volume guarantees from BBW for a set number of years. The minus: spending millions to relocate production and buy new equipment.</p><p> Rieke Packaging, which makes dispensing pumps for soap bottles, didn&#39;t know if it was going to be worth the investment. At the time, Rieke made the pump at factories in China. Rieke had an existing factory a few hours away in Indiana that could potentially supply the park, but Bath &amp; Body Works said it wanted factories on-site.</p><p> “From a supplier perspective, there was a lot of resistance,” said Craig Miller, who worked for Rieke at the time and now works in supply chain and manufacturing for a pharmaceutical company. “You want us to buy more equipment. Our lease rate is going to be double what it&#39;s going to be in rural Indiana. Come on, that doesn&#39;t sound any fun.”</p><p> Rieke decided to make the several-million dollar investment in New Albany. “It was too big of an opportunity to pass up,” Miller said. </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="466" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-822319?width=700&amp;height=466" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Corwin Strong works on quality control at Rieke in New Albany.</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> Moving production to Ohio wasn&#39;t easy. Factories had to contend with planning officials, high labor and construction costs and even endangered bats.</p><p> Jeff Stouffer worked for Bath &amp; Body Works in new product launches and later joined a supplier that made perfumes and filled bottles, which opened up a new factory at the campus around 2015. He and other executives met with city and business park officials more than a dozen times to discuss the aesthetics of the relatively small factory, negotiating over everything from the color of the walls to the size of the company&#39;s sign. It was like a homeowners&#39; association on steroids, he said.</p><p> “They are very rigid about what it looks like,” he said.</p><p> The possible presence of a species of endangered bats prevented the removal of trees on the site, delaying construction for several months.</p><p> Still, almost every company has expanded beyond their initial investment.</p><p> “It&#39;s going to be a 2- to 3-year heavy lift for a payout in 5 to 10 years from now,” Stouffer said.</p><p> Keeping costs down was the biggest challenge.</p><p> Not every production step took place in Ohio at first. Rieke initially molded two outer plastic parts in New Albany, which could be made from any number of colors. It would then attach them to the inner core of the pump, which was still made in China.</p><p> Around 2020, Bath &amp; Body Works said it really wanted the entire foaming soap pump to be produced in the US BBW also didn&#39;t want to pay more than the approximately 20 to 25 cents per unit it was paying, according to Will Nguyen, an engineer who then worked for Rieke and now works as a consulting engineer.</p><p> The two sides negotiated a multiyear supplier agreement to bring pump engine production to the campus from China. For a few months, it wasn&#39;t clear if that would happen, said Nguyen. </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="466" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-822332?width=700&amp;height=466" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Bottles of Bath &amp; Body Works soap at KDC/One.</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> Rieke agreed to make the entire pump in Ohio at essentially the same unit cost, and Bath &amp; Body Works helped Rieke get access to volume guarantees and global purchasing and supplier deals with other companies, said Nguyen.</p><p> Now Rieke had to figure out how to make the pumps in Ohio—profitably. They turned to automation.</p><p> In China, building the 13-part pump was a manual process using lots of workers who handled tiny springs and balls. “We cannot replicate the manual process that was done overseas in central Ohio,” said Mark Box, an executive of TriMas Packaging, the parent of Rieke—but getting machines to replicate that work was complicated. “You&#39;ve got very small parts, moving very quickly. The slightest thing can cause a jam.”</p><p> The machines had to make a pump tight enough to keep the liquid inside but not so tight that it won&#39;t operate. The machines also had to deal with differences in plastics and other raw materials from shipment to shipment.</p><p> Nguyen estimates that production in the US employs around 10 people and required $12 million in capital investment, versus employing around 50 people with under $2 million in investment for similar production capacity in China.</p><p> The automation and proximity means that pumps and their parts can arrive and be fully created in under a month, compared with five months previously. Rieke sells around 300 million pumps to Bath &amp; Body Works a year.</p><p> New Albany thinks the beauty campus can be a model for other companies and communities. It has attracted an <a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/AMGN" class="company-name">Amgen</a> pharmaceutical plant. Last year Intel chose New Albany as the site of a <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/intel-to-invest-at-least-20-billion-in-ohio-chip-making-facility-11642750760?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">$20 billion semiconductor facility</a> . The company said the Intel plant would attract dozens of new local suppliers, including semiconductor equipment makers and other materials providers. </p><div class="media-object scope-
          bleed
"><figure class="media-object-image img-bleed"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="1260" height="840" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-822327?width=1260&amp;height=840" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> People work on molds for Bath &amp; Body Works bottles at Axium in New Albany.</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> The success of the park, and its thousands of employees during the peak season, means that some of the closely located manufacturers are worried about labor shortages. Bath &amp; Body Works has recently allowed some suppliers to open up factories in other parts of Ohio to attract new workers.</p><p> BBW&#39;s strategy today revolves around the unique properties of its beauty park: new products, delivered quickly. Bath &amp; Body Works regularly rolls out fresh aromas and places a premium on fast design and production. This model allows BBW to charge premium prices and avoid discounts and leftovers, and helps cover the added cost of local manufacturing.</p><p> The Wild Sand aroma (fragrance notes: prickly pear fruit, cactus flower and warm agave nectar), launched earlier this month, is available as a hand soap, candle, shower gel, perfume, sanitizer spray, body lotion and self tanner.</p><p> Unlike most retailers, which preorder all of their products for the season months in advance, Bath &amp; Body Works aims to preorder around two-thirds. It then closely monitors sales and places additional “instant” orders for winning products.</p><p> “Within literally a week, that&#39;s what&#39;s getting shipped,” said Nicholas Whitley, chief executive at soap maker and filler KDC/One.</p><p> Being co-located means manufacturers can use a campus shipping service to easily send samples to the next stage in the process or to a Bath &amp; Body Works executive for signoff, no overnight shipping required. How something smells, feels or looks in a store is hard to relay over Zoom calls.</p><p> “There are glitters, holographics that don&#39;t translate as well,” said Tom DeCicco, a graphics manager at label maker CCL Label. “You can&#39;t get that in the picture.”</p><p> Write to Austen Hufford at <a href="mailto:austen.hufford@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">austen.hufford@wsj.com</a></p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Tue, 25 Jul 2023 09:30:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/bath-body-works-us-manufacturing-413cf9d0</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/bath-body-works-us-manufacturing-413cf9d0<author><![CDATA[Austen Hufford]]></author><category> leder</category><category> gfx-contrib</category><category> photo-commission</category><category> wsjwashington</category><category> Retail/Wholesale</category><category> Cosmetics/Perfume Retailing</category><category> Clothing Retail</category><category> Specialty Retailing</category><category> Retail</category><category>企业/行业新闻</category><category>Supply Chain</category><category> SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category> Bath &amp; Body Works</category><category> BBWI</category><category>公司的</category><category>行业新闻</category><category>supply chain</category><category> retail</category><category> wholesale</category><category> cosmetics</category><category> perfume retailing</category><category> clothing retail</category><category> specialty retailing </category></item><item><title><![CDATA[Ukraine’s Stalled Offensive Puts Biden in Uneasy Political Position]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div> Administration&#39;s hopes that Kyiv could negotiate with Moscow fade with slow progress on the ground <figure><img src="https://images.wsj.net/im-822600/?width=1278&amp;size=1" alt="乌克兰士兵向乌克兰东部扎波罗热地区的俄罗斯阵地开火。" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><figcaption> Ukrainian soldiers firing on Russian positions in the Zaporizhzhia region of eastern Ukraine. Dmytro Smoliyenko/UKRINFORM/Zuma Press <span>Dmytro Smoliyenko/UKRINFORM/Zuma Press</span> </figcaption></figure><!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001079729"></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001079729"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"> By <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/gordon-lubold" itemprop="url" rel="author">Gordon Lubold</a></span> , <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/michael-r-gordon" itemprop="url" rel="author">Michael R. Gordon</a></span> , <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/warren-p-strobel" itemprop="url" rel="author">Warren P. Strobel</a></span> and</div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1"> Updated July 25, 2023 12:00 am ET </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/ukraines-stalled-offensive-puts-biden-in-uneasy-political-position-6f686ab5"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          bigtophero
"></div><p> The slow pace of <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/russia-seeks-to-divert-ukrainian-forces-away-from-counteroffensive-80580e89?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">Ukraine&#39;s counteroffensive</a> against entrenched Russian invaders is dimming hopes that negotiations for an end to the fighting could come this year and raising the specter of an open-ended conflict, according to Western officials.</p><p> <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/ukraines-lack-of-weaponry-and-training-risks-stalemate-in-fight-with-russia-f51ecf9?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">A potential stalemate</a> would test President Biden&#39;s stated strategy of pouring billions of dollars in military aid into Ukraine, to enable Kyiv to negotiate with Russia from a position of strength. It could also challenge the West&#39;s continuing ability to supply weaponry that is already in short supply, and provide political fodder to those opposing US support for the war.</p><p> “Obviously it&#39;s easier to provide more support when things are going well,” said John Herbst, a former US ambassador to Ukraine and an advocate of expanding military assistance to Kyiv. But the Biden administration doesn&#39;t have much choice other than to continue providing weapons, he said.</p><p> Backing away from Ukraine and allowing even a partial Russian victory “would be the signature failure of Biden foreign policy that would dwarf the Afghan withdrawal,” added Herbst, who is now at the Washington-based Atlantic Council think tank.</p><p> The US stay-the-course strategy holds some risks, however. Biden has staked his foreign policy credentials on a conflict that he describes as a battle between democracy and authoritarianism. He has directed more than $43 billion in security assistance to Kyiv, but is facing <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/mccarthy-opposes-extra-ukraine-spending-after-debt-deal-cf967c6?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">challenges in Congress</a> from some members of the Republican Party. </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="466" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-822598?width=700&amp;height=466" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> President Biden has directed more than $43 billion in security assistance to Ukraine.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Henrik Montgomery/Zuma Press</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> On Thursday, 13 Senate Republicans backed an amendment to the annual defense spending bill that would have limited the availability of funds for Ukraine. The amendment failed, and support for Ukraine remains strong among other Republicans in Congress.</p><p> As Biden moves toward a presidential contest next year, Russian President <a href="https://www.wsj.com/topics/person/vladimir-putin">Vladimir Putin</a> has more of an incentive to try to outlast the West. Two of the top contenders for the Republican nomination—former President <a href="https://www.wsj.com/topics/person/donald-trump">Donald Trump</a> and Florida Gov. <a href="https://www.wsj.com/topics/person/ron-desantis">Ron DeSantis</a> —have suggested they might temper military support for Ukraine.</p><p> Russia has also shown little inclination to negotiate. With the invasion of Ukraine bogged down, <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/russia-arrests-militant-right-wing-critic-igor-girkin-in-widening-crackdown-3b6308?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">Putin is facing critics</a> inside his country who say he hasn&#39;t pursued the war aggressively enough.</p><p> “The Russians are more than happy to talk about Ukraine&#39;s capitulation,” said Thomas Graham, a distinguished fellow at the Council on Foreign Relations. “I don&#39;t think they are seriously interested in any talks about a resolution of the Ukraine crisis short of that at this point.”</p><p> Ukraine&#39;s counteroffensive, launched at the start of June, is aimed at retaking some of the nearly 20% of Ukrainian territory occupied by Moscow. While Ukraine has seized back some territory, it hasn&#39;t yet achieved a breakthrough that might force Russia to the negotiating table. </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><div class="media-object-video"><div class="wsj-media-summary clearfix"><div class="strap-container"><h4 class="strap" itemprop="description"></h4></div></div><iframe width="400" height="225" src="https://video-api.wsj.com/api-video/player/v3/iframe.html?guid=C97C88D4-572D-4836-8A1A-666E07F3B3AE&amp;height=225&amp;width=400&amp;plid=video_amp&amp;chainVideos=true&amp;parentUrl=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.wsj.com%2Famp%2Farticles%2Fukraines-stalled-offensive-puts-biden-in-uneasy-political-position-6f686ab5&amp;a=a" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe><p class="imageCaption"> Russia accused Ukraine of launching a drone attack on Moscow early Monday. The Russian Defense Ministry said the drones were intercepted, and Moscow&#39;s mayor said no serious damage or injuries were reported. Photo: AFP/Getty Images<span class="imageCredit">
        
        
        </span></p></div></div><p>“My hope is and my expectation is you&#39;ll see that Ukraine makes significant progress on their offensive and it generates a negotiated settlement somewhere along the line,” Biden said during <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/biden-visit-cements-finlands-pivot-away-from-neutrality-3fd65237?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">his visit to Helsinki</a> earlier this month.</p><p> With neither Russia nor Ukraine inclined to negotiate, the White House has few options for now but to stay the course, hoping for an eventual battlefield breakthrough against entrenched Russian forces—or new political cracks in Moscow.</p><p> US officials acknowledge the counteroffensive is going slowly, but say it is too soon to assess the effectiveness until Ukraine commits more of its combat brigades, especially those that have been trained by the US at bases in Europe in armored maneuver warfare.</p><p> “If they commit their reserves and their reserves aren&#39;t successful, then we will have to determine the way ahead,” said one US official.</p><p> In an interview Sunday on CNN, Secretary of State Antony Blinken said the offensive is still in its early days and Ukraine has “already taken back about 50% of what was initially seized” since February 2022, when Russia launched its full-scale invasion. </p><div class="media-object scope-
          bleed
"><figure class="media-object-image img-bleed"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="1260" height="840" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-822597?width=1260&amp;height=840" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Workers clearing rubble after a strike in Odesa, Ukraine. Russia has shown little inclination to negotiate.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: oleksandr gimanov/Agence France-Presse/Getty Images </p></figcaption></figure></div><div class="media-object scope-
          bleed
"><figure class="media-object-image img-bleed"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="1260" height="902" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-822596?width=1260&amp;height=902" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Ukrainian soldiers in eastern Ukraine. US officials acknowledge the counteroffensive is going slowly.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Oleksandr Ratushniak/REUTERS</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> Kyiv&#39;s mission is a difficult one, said a senior European official, who indicated his government had little expectation Ukraine&#39;s forces could evict Russian troops from all of eastern Ukraine or <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/blasts-hit-military-base-in-russian-occupied-crimea-c9c1ffc1?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">retake Crimea</a> . While a surprise is possible, he acknowledged, it isn&#39;t necessarily likely.</p><p> “We are not expecting that they will be able to recover all the territory that was lost to Russia, especially if you are considering Crimea and even the territory which was lost in 2014 with Donbas,” said the official, whose government is among Ukraine&#39;s strong supporters.</p><p> Another challenge facing the US and its allies are dwindling reserves of key weaponry, a shortfall Washington recently sought to partly address by <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/u-s-to-send-cluster-munitions-to-bolster-ukraines-fight-against-dug-in-russians-d2dd292f?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">supplying Kyiv with cluster munitions.</a></p><div class="media-object scope-web
          wrap
"><div class="media-object-rich-text"><h4>SHARE YOUR THOUGHTS</h4><p> <em>How much support should the US give to Ukraine? Join the conversation below.</em></p></div></div><p> Speaking to reporters last week at the Aspen Security Forum, UK Foreign Secretary</p> James Cleverly said the US and the West must continue to supply as much and as quickly possible to Ukraine.<p></p><p> “People say, &#39;Yeah, but you know what, we can&#39;t leave the cupboard bare. You got to save it for a rainy day,&#39;” he said. “I mean, this is the rainy day.”</p><p> One Western diplomat in Washington said the US may have to accept that the war in Ukraine isn&#39;t going to end soon, and allies need to prepare to supply Kyiv for a conflict that lasts for years.</p><p> “The only real response is an industrial mobilization that will give Ukrainians, and the Russians, a clear message that the Ukrainians will always have plenty of what they need,” the diplomat said.</p><p> The question is whether the US and its allies have the resolve to continue support, or even expand it, if the offensive continues to fall short of expectations. High on Ukraine&#39;s wishlist are <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/u-s-close-to-approving-long-range-atacms-missiles-to-bolster-ukraines-fight-cc4e389c?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">US-made ATACMS</a> long-range missiles and faster acquisition of F-16 fighters.</p><p> Speaking last week at the Aspen Security Forum, Canada&#39;s Deputy Prime Minister Chrystia Freeland openly worried about the ability of Western allies to stay the course.</p><p> “My biggest fear for Ukraine, actually, is us,” she said.</p><p class="articleTagLine"> —Alan Cullison, William Mauldin and Sharon Weinberger contributed to this article.</p><p> Write to Gordon Lubold at <a href="mailto:gordon.lubold@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">gordon.lubold@wsj.com</a> , Michael R. Gordon at <a href="mailto:michael.gordon@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">michael.gordon@wsj.com</a> and Warren P. Strobel at <a href="mailto:Warren.Strobel@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">Warren.Strobel@wsj.com</a></p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Tue, 25 Jul 2023 04:00:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/ukraines-stalled-offensive-puts-biden-in-uneasy-political-position-6f686ab5</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/ukraines-stalled-offensive-puts-biden-in-uneasy-political-position-6f686ab5<author><![CDATA[Gordon LuboldMichael R. GordonWarren P. Strobel]]></author><category> ukraine</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>国家/公共安全</category><category>International Relations</category><category>政治/国际关系</category><category>国内政治</category><category>Risk News</category><category> Military Action</category><category> SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category> President Biden</category><category> John Herbst</category><category> Thomas Graham</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>国家的</category><category>公安</category><category>国际关系</category><category>政治</category><category>国内政治</category><category>risk news</category><category> military action </category></item><item><title><![CDATA[Israel Approves Part of Netanyahu’s Controversial Judicial Overhaul]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div> Prime minister&#39;s coalition votes in favor of legislation after lawmakers failed to reach compromise <!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001079176"><div class="is-lead-inset"><div class="media-object scope-
          header
"><div class="media-object-video"><div class="wsj-media-summary clearfix"><div class="strap-container"><h4 class="strap" itemprop="description"></h4></div></div><iframe width="400" height="225" src="https://video-api.wsj.com/api-video/player/v3/iframe.html?guid=E3E72531-794A-477C-836E-5960EF41E94A&amp;height=225&amp;width=400&amp;plid=video_amp&amp;chainVideos=true&amp;parentUrl=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.wsj.com%2Famp%2Farticles%2Fisrael-netanyahu-government-judicial-overhaul-protests-862dffd3&amp;a=a" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe><p class="imageCaption"> Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu&#39;s coalition on Monday passed the first bill in a contentious judicial overhaul that seeks to limit the power of the Supreme Court. WSJ&#39;s Dov Lieber reports from Jerusalem. Photo: Corinna Kern/Reuters<span class="imageCredit">
        
        
        </span></p></div></div></div></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001079176"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"> By <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/dov-lieber" itemprop="url" rel="author">Dov Lieber</a></span> and <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/shayndi-raice" itemprop="url" rel="author">Shayndi Raice</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1"> Updated July 24, 2023 6:19 pm ET </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/israel-netanyahu-government-judicial-overhaul-protests-862dffd3"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><p> JERUSALEM—Israel&#39;s Parliament passed <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/israels-netanyahu-pushes-ahead-with-vote-on-judicial-overhaul-as-protests-intensify-d29b1b55?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">a divisive judicial overhaul</a> , defying <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/israel-protests-flare-up-in-new-push-to-stop-judicial-overhaul-9f939aac?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">months of protests</a> and plunging the country further into a political crisis that has exposed rifts over its identity and raised fears about its national security.</p><p> The law&#39;s passage on Monday by Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu&#39;s coalition—without any opposition support—marks a pivotal juncture for Israeli society, setting up a potential showdown with the country&#39;s Supreme Court, the institution whose power <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/netanyahu-revives-judicial-overhaul-stripped-of-most-controversial-piece-33160de?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">the law was designed to curb</a> . It presents a decisive moment for thousands of military reservists who have said they would quit and the business, union leaders and medical professionals who have threatened mass work stoppages.</p><p> And it could complicate Israel&#39;s <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/biden-netanyahu-agree-to-meet-later-this-year-247c33f7?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">relationship with the US</a> and other allies, who have long considered it the only full-fledged democracy in the Middle East. President Biden took the unusual step of calling on Netanyahu to compromise before passing the legislation. The White House released a statement calling the bill&#39;s passage “unfortunate.”</p><p> Voting in favor of the bill were Netanyahu&#39;s entire coalition of 64 lawmakers, widely viewed as the most right wing, nationalist and religious in the country&#39;s 75-year history. They cheered the law, which takes away the Supreme Court&#39;s ability to nullify government decisions it finds “unreasonable in the extreme”—a concept they said was nebulous and allowed liberal judges to overturn the will of an increasingly right-wing electorate. </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="466" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-822518?width=700&amp;height=466" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Israeli lawmakers celebrated on Monday, after approving part of Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu&#39;s judicial overhaul.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Maya Alleruzzo/Associated Press</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> It is the first in a series of laws the coalition wants to pass to limit the power of the court system. Next up is a bill that would give lawmakers more power to select judges—a move that is more contentious than the bill passed on Monday. It could be voted on in the fall.</p><p> “We made the first move in the historic process of fixing the justice system,” said Justice Minister Yariv Levin, widely considered the architect of the overhaul.</p><p> In a speech Monday night, Netanyahu said that his coalition would continue to reach out to the opposition in order to reach agreements on any judicial legislation going forward.</p><p> “No side will control the court. This cannot happen. It will not happen on our watch,” Netanyahu said.</p><p> The legislation passed after talks to forge a compromise collapsed. Opposition lawmakers walked out of the room, boycotting the vote.</p><p> Mass demonstrations broke out across the country Monday, and more were planned late into the night. Police worked to prevent protesters from storming the Knesset. Tens of thousands shouted “Democracy!” and blew loud horns as they filled the streets of Jerusalem near the Knesset and other government buildings.</p><p> “We refuse to accept this,” said Roee Basha, 34. “It is clear to us all that there is no alternative. We either escalate or we leave the country.”</p><div class="media-object scope-web,mobileapps
          wrap
"></div><p> Police said dozens of protesters were arrested, with authorities forcibly removing some demonstrators blocking streets in Tel Aviv, according to footage aired on Israel&#39;s Channel 12. Police used water cannons to disperse protesters in Tel Aviv, the footage showed.</p><p></p> Yair Lapid, the leader of the opposition, called passage of the legislation “the destruction of Israeli democracy.”<p></p><p> “We will not give up,” he said. “We will not surrender. We will not let them turn Israel into a broken, undemocratic country, which is run by hatred and extremism.”</p><p> Monday&#39;s legislative action could set off an extraordinary series of events that will test Israel&#39;s unity, including a challenge to the law in front of the Supreme Court. A nongovernmental organization said it petitioned the court Monday, claiming that the law fundamentally changes the nature of Israeli democracy and that the process to pass the law was flawed.</p><p> “We are moving one step closer to a constitutional showdown,” said Yuval Shany, a law professor at Hebrew University in Jerusalem. </p><div class="media-object scope-
          bleed
"><figure class="media-object-image img-bleed"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="1260" height="841" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-822439?width=1260&amp;height=841" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Israeli police blocked protesters during a demonstration outside the Knesset, Israel&#39;s Parliament, in Jerusalem, on Monday.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Kobi Wolf/Bloomberg News</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> Monday&#39;s legislation was an amendment to one of Israel&#39;s so-called basic laws—piecemeal legislation that is the closest thing the country has to a constitution. Shany said justices have never struck down a basic law but have suggested in various rulings that the court has the right to do so if it fundamentally changes the nature of democracy in Israel or if it abuses the constitutional process.</p><p> The bill&#39;s passage represents a challenge for Israel&#39;s military, often called a “people&#39;s army” for its reliance on volunteer reserves. The judicial overhaul has alienated many military reservists, some of whom see the move as <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/israel-ultra-orthodox-haredim-military-service-supreme-court-of-ultra-orthodox-jews-shakes-israels-sense-of-identity-b3155e01?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">a power grab by ultra-Orthodox Jews</a> , the vast majority of whom don&#39;t serve in the army.</p><p> Thousands of military reservists said this week they <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/netanyahu-faces-fresh-stand-off-with-israeli-reservists-over-judicial-overhaul-b974d3f5?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">would stop reporting for volunteer duty</a> if the legislation passed, although it remains to be seen if they will carry through on that promise. Military officials have warned that the legislation was undermining unity within the military.</p><p> “I have no words. I want to cry,” Ben Levy, a reserve combat soldier and psychology student from Netanya, said after Monday&#39;s vote. </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="466" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-822441?width=700&amp;height=466" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Israeli police trying to move protesters blocking the road leading to Parliament in Jerusalem.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Ilia Yefimovich/Zuma Press</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> He said it was likely that many more reservists will announce they won&#39;t serve any more and many will do it quietly by finding an excuse not to show up.</p><p> Netanyahu, the country&#39;s longest-serving prime minister now in his sixth term, brought the judicial legislation back from defeat after his government first tried to pass a different package of bills in March. He postponed the effort after mass protests and a general strike paralyzed the nation, but he said last month that he would pass the overhaul in modified form.</p><p> Netanyahu, who was released from the hospital Monday after being fitted for a pacemaker, hasn&#39;t historically been an advocate for changing the judiciary, but he was under intense pressure to pass it from his right flank, which gives him his narrow parliamentary majority.</p><p> On the other side were Biden, business leaders and hundreds of thousands of protesters who have demonstrated every weekend for more than six months. On Monday, the country&#39;s main labor union, the Histadrut, said it was preparing for the possibility of calling a general strike, potentially crippling the country again. </p><div class="media-object scope-
          bleed
"><figure class="media-object-image img-bleed"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="1260" height="840" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-822442?width=1260&amp;height=840" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> An aerial view shows tents erected in demonstration against the government&#39;s judicial overhaul near the Knesset in Jerusalem.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: ILAN ROSENBERG/REUTERS</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> The debate over the judicial legislation has cast a light on Israel&#39;s societal divide over what it means to be both <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/israeli-judicial-overhaul-pits-secular-religious-communities-against-each-other-a4177c16?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">a Jewish and a democratic state</a> .该国在成立之初的几十年里是由主要是东欧血统的世俗社会主义者建立和控制的。他们设想了一个文化上犹太教但社会上自由民主的国家。近几十年来，代表以色列右翼的不同阶层——宗教犹太复国主义者、定居者、极端正统派和中东裔犹太人——之间的联盟在数量和力量上都在增长。 Netanyahu&#39;s Likud party, which is itself secular, has united those segments on the right into a political powerhouse.</p><p> “This is a clash between the Israelis and the Jews,” said Gideon Rahat, chair of the political science department at the Hebrew University in Jerusalem.他说，以色列人代表了设想世俗犹太复国主义国家的创始人，而犹太人则是那些想要重建 2000 年前统治这片土地的犹太王国的人。</p><p> “It&#39;s a clash between a more civil identity and a more religious identity,” he said.</p><p> In a country without a powerful presidency, the Supreme Court has long been the only check on the government&#39;s ruling coalition, often thwarting decisions by right-wing governments in recent years. One recent example was when the court nullified Netanyahu&#39;s appointment of a key ultraorthodox ally who was convicted of corruption and tax evasion to be interior, health and finance minister.</p><p> Israel&#39;s finance minister, Bezalel Smotrich, said the coalition was trying to “restore the balance between the branches of government.”</p><p> “Together we will continue to make repairs responsibly,” he said. </p><div class="media-object scope-
          bleed
"><figure class="media-object-image img-bleed"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="1260" height="840" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-822521?width=1260&amp;height=840" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Protesters are sprayed by a police water cannon during a demonstration near the Knesset in Jerusalem.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: RONEN ZVULUN/REUTERS</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> Hodaya Ganon, 27, a social worker from the northern Israeli city of Haifa, said passing the legislation Monday counted as long-awaited recognition of right-wing voters. “Until now, all previous right-wing governments have bent to the will of the other side at the expense of their voters, despite having won fairly and democratically,” she said.</p><p> It is, in part, Netanyahu&#39;s legal troubles that have brought the country to this point. Throughout most of his two decades in power, Netanyahu built coalitions from the right, center and the left. After his 2019 indictment on bribery and fraud—which he denies—his former centrist partners and even some on the right refused to sit in a government with him, leading him to briefly lose power. When he returned as premier late last year, he built a coalition that included two ultraorthodox political parties and an alliance of ultranationalists.</p><p> Shlomit Ravitsky Tur-Paz, a legal and Jewish studies scholar with the Jerusalem-based Israel Democracy Institute, said that even though the right wing has been in power for decades, many voters feel as if the country is ruled by secular, liberal elites and that is most evident in the power wielded by the court.</p><p> “They still feel they are the ones who don&#39;t have the power,” she said. “So that&#39;s what they are trying to change now.”</p><p class="articleTagLine"> —Ari Flanzraich 对本文做出了贡献。</p><p> Write to Dov Lieber at <a href="mailto:dov.lieber@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">dov.lieber@wsj.com</a> and Shayndi Raice at <a href="mailto:Shayndi.Raice@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">Shayndi.Raice@wsj.com</a></p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Mon, 24 Jul 2023 22:19:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/israel-netanyahu-government-judicial-overhaul-protests-862dffd3</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/israel-netanyahu-government-judicial-overhaul-protests-862dffd3<author><![CDATA[Dov LieberShayndi Raice]]></author><category> wsjworld</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>Civil Unrest</category><category>国家/公共安全</category><category>社会/社区</category><category>政治/国际关系</category><category>国内政治</category><category>Risk News</category><category>社会问题</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>本杰明·内塔尼亚胡</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>civil unrest</category><category>国家的</category><category>公安</category><category>社会</category><category>社区</category><category>政治</category><category>国际关系</category><category>国内政治</category><category>risk news</category><category>社会问题</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[North Korea Hasn’t Answered U.S.’s Calls on Detained Soldier]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div> No &#39;new communications&#39; since contact soon after US soldier went across the border, State Department says <!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001079129"><div class="is-lead-inset"><div class="media-object scope-
          header
"><div class="media-object-video"><div class="wsj-media-summary clearfix"><div class="strap-container"><h4 class="strap" itemprop="description"></h4></div></div><iframe width="400" height="225" src="https://video-api.wsj.com/api-video/player/v3/iframe.html?guid=D218996D-CA76-4EBA-85A1-7ED736A7A86E&amp;height=225&amp;width=400&amp;plid=video_amp&amp;chainVideos=true&amp;parentUrl=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.wsj.com%2Famp%2Farticles%2Fu-s-and-north-korea-start-talking-about-american-soldier-who-crossed-the-border-6be51607&amp;a=a" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe><p class="imageCaption"> A State Department spokesman said the US hasn&#39;t received a response from North Korea regarding the whereabouts of American soldier Travis King, who was detained there. Photo: Ahn Young-Joon/Associated Press<span class="imageCredit">
        
        
        </span></p></div></div></div></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001079129"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"> By <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/dasl-yoon" itemprop="url" rel="author">Dasl Yoon</a></span> in Seoul and <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/gordon-lubold" itemprop="url" rel="author">Gordon Lubold</a></span> in Washington</div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1"> Updated July 24, 2023 5:49 pm ET </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/u-s-and-north-korea-start-talking-about-american-soldier-who-crossed-the-border-6be51607"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><p> The US has reached out to North Korea about <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/north-korea-us-national-custody-b53b4449?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">an American soldier</a> who crossed the border from South Korea last week, but so far Pyongyang hasn&#39;t responded, US officials said.</p><p> British Army Lieutenant General Andrew Harrison told a briefing on Monday that the US has attempted to have conversations with the North Koreans using a communications line established under the armistice agreement that ended combat in the 1950-53 Korean War. US officials said that the US had reached out through at least two channels, but that Pyongyang hadn&#39;t engaged.</p><p> “We have relayed messages through multiple channels to [North Korea] that the individual crossed on his own and we want him returned quickly and safely,” a US official said. “We also asked for more information on his welfare.” The official said that the US knows the message has been received by the North Koreans, but wouldn&#39;t elaborate further.</p><p> The United Nations command in Seoul, which is led by an American general who also leads US Forces Korea, has made attempts to reach out to Pyongyang. The White House, using Sweden as an intermediary, has also made similar attempts, officials said.</p><p> A spokesman for the US State Department also said the UN and the North Koreans hadn&#39;t been in regular contact since King&#39;s initial flight. The spokesman, Matt Miller, denied reports that the UN command had been in regular touch with the North Koreans, suggesting there had been a “misinterpretation.”</p><p> “I&#39;m not aware of any new communications, other than those that happened in the very early hours or early days after he went across the border,” said Matt Miller. </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="480" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-822426?width=700&amp;height=480" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> British Army Lieutenant General Andrew Harrison, who is deputy commander of the United Nations Command, spoke at a briefing Monday.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: jung yeon-je/Agence France-Presse/Getty Images</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> Private 2nd Class Travis King, 23 years old, has been detained in North Korea since he crossed the border while on a tour last Tuesday of the Joint Security Area, part of the Demilitarized Zone separating the two Koreas.</p><p> “The primary concern for us is Private King&#39;s welfare,” Harrison said. He said he remains optimistic, but declined to provide details on the talks, citing their sensitivity.</p><p> The day before he crossed the border, King had been set to fly Texas for disciplinary actions and a potential discharge following <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/travis-king-u-s-soldier-held-in-north-korea-had-been-detained-in-south-korea-4cded529?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">two alleged assaults last year</a> , officials said last week. He had been held at a detention facility in South Korea for 47 days.</p><p> North Korea has said nothing publicly about King.</p><p> <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/u-s-soldiers-crossing-into-north-korea-points-to-security-gaps-576b7733?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none" rel="noreferrer noopener">King&#39;s crossing</a> has raised questions about the US military&#39;s handling of personnel at overseas bases. He had been escorted to Incheon Airport last Monday by US service members, who left after King passed through security checkpoints. King told airline staff he couldn&#39;t locate his passport and slipped out of the airport. He headed to the Joint Security Area as part of a tour group the next day.</p><p> A spokesman for the US Forces Korea, which oversees the 28,500 American military personnel stationed in the country, said the incident remains under investigation.</p><p> King allegedly assaulted a South Korean citizen last September and the next month was involved in another assault and damaged a police car by kicking it, for which he was fined $4,000. Army Secretary</p> Christine Wormuth speculated at a news conference last Thursday that King had been grappling with the consequences he would face upon returning to the US<p></p><p> North Korea watchers say King&#39;s voluntary entry into the country may make winning his release difficult. In the past, North Korea has used defections by US soldiers as a propaganda opportunity, portraying Americans as growing disenchanted with capitalism. Army Sgt. Charles Jenkins, who deserted his post in South Korea and fled to the North in 1965, became a familiar figure in North Korean films, cast as a capitalist villain.</p><p> North Korea has refused to engage in dialogue with the US since <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/even-before-trump-and-kim-met-nuclear-talks-had-run-aground-11551487094?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">nuclear talks collapsed in Hanoi in 2019</a> . In recent weeks, high-level North Korean officials have released statements lashing out at Washington for deploying to South Korea such strategic assets as the <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/u-s-nuclear-capable-boomer-sub-visits-south-korea-for-first-time-in-decades-dc4a8187?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none" rel="noreferrer noopener">USS Kentucky</a> , a nuclear-capable submarine. Last Thursday, North Korea&#39;s defense minister warned that the sub&#39;s presence could be grounds for Pyongyang to use nuclear weapons.</p><p> On Monday, the USS Annapolis, a nuclear-propelled US submarine, arrived at a port on South Korea&#39;s Jeju Island as an additional show of force against North Korea&#39;s growing nuclear and missile threats. A spokesman for South Korea&#39;s navy said the US and South Korea were discussing whether to involve the submarine in training.</p><p> The Kim regime has ramped up missile tests ahead of a major holiday it calls Victory Day on July 27. At 11:55 pm local time on Monday, North Korea fired two short-range ballistic missiles off its east coast, South Korea&#39;s military said. Rodong Sinmun, Pyongyang&#39;s main state-run newspaper, published an editorial on Monday that claimed military buildup is necessary to preserve peace.</p><p> “There can be no end to strengthening military power,” Rodong Sinmun said.</p><p> Write to Dasl Yoon at <a href="mailto:dasl.yoon@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">dasl.yoon@wsj.com</a> and Gordon Lubold at <a href="mailto:gordon.lubold@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">gordon.lubold@wsj.com</a></p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Mon, 24 Jul 2023 21:49:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/us-and-north-korea-start-talking-about-american-soldier-who-crossed-the-border-6be51607</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/us-and-north-korea-start-talking-about-american-soldier-who-crossed-the-border-6be51607<author><![CDATA[Dasl YoonGordon Lubold]]></author><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>国家/公共安全</category><category>武装部队</category><category>International Relations</category><category>政治/国际关系</category><category>Risk News</category><category> Military Action</category><category> SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category> Andrew Harrison</category><category> Travis King</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>国家的</category><category>公安</category><category>武装部队</category><category>国际关系</category><category>政治</category><category>risk news</category><category> military action</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[FDIC Scolds Banks for Manipulating Deposit Data]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div> Lenders lowered their uninsured deposits by nearly $200 billion after bank failures <!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001080330"><div class="is-lead-inset"><div class="media-object scope-
          header
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="860" height="588" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-822609?width=860&amp;height=588" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Bank of America lowered its stated uninsured deposits by more than any other bank in a Journal analysis of FDIC filings.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Justin Sullivan/Getty Images </p></figcaption></figure></div></div></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001080330"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"> By <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/jonathan-weil" itemprop="url" rel="author">Jonathan Weil</a></span> and <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/shane-shifflett" itemprop="url" rel="author">Shane Shifflett</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1"> Updated July 24, 2023 5:21 pm ET </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/fdic-scolds-banks-for-manipulating-deposit-data-f7fe93d7"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><p> When Silicon Valley Bank ran into financial trouble, its customers ran for the exits because <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/the-pain-of-silicon-valley-banks-collapse-is-being-felt-by-these-depositors-f18c0bd4?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">most of their deposits weren&#39;t insured</a> . In the weeks after, dozens of banks tweaked their numbers to reduce the portions of their deposits that they said were uninsured.</p><p> On Monday, the Federal Deposit Insurance Corp. sent a warning to US banks not to take liberties with their deposit numbers. A Wall Street Journal analysis of the banks&#39; filings with the FDIC shows that <a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/BAC" class="company-name">Bank of America</a> and <a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/HBAN" class="company-name">Huntington National Bank</a> had among the biggest revisions to their uninsured-deposit numbers.</p><p> Since <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/silicon-valley-bank-svb-financial-what-is-happening-299e9b65?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">Silicon Valley Bank&#39;s collapse</a> in March, 47 banks restated their Dec. 31 uninsured-deposit figures downward by a total of $198 billion, the Journal analysis showed. At Silicon Valley Bank, 88% of the deposits were uninsured at year-end.</p><p> Many of the banks that changed their numbers tried to include an unusual type of account in the category of deposits insured by the FDIC. Typically the FDIC insures deposits up to $250,000. These accounts, often from government entities, generally exceeded that amount, but the banks put collateral behind them, effectively guaranteeing the depositors would be paid back if the bank failed. </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><div class="media-object-video"><div class="wsj-media-summary clearfix"><div class="strap-container"><h4 class="strap" itemprop="description"></h4></div></div><iframe width="400" height="225" src="https://video-api.wsj.com/api-video/player/v3/iframe.html?guid=13078590-113A-43AC-B5B7-6E1A055FB210&amp;height=225&amp;width=400&amp;plid=video_amp&amp;chainVideos=true&amp;parentUrl=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.wsj.com%2Famp%2Farticles%2Ffdic-scolds-banks-for-manipulating-deposit-data-f7fe93d7&amp;a=a" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe><p class="imageCaption"> The Federal Deposit Insurance Corporation is doing what it was designed to do when banks like Silicon Valley and Signature go under: cover insured deposits. Here&#39;s how the FDIC works and why it was created. Photo illustration: Madeline Marshall<span class="imageCredit">
        
        
        </span></p></div></div><p>In a letter to banks, the FDIC said that only deposits that it insured could be called insured deposits. “The existence of collateral has no bearing on the portion of a deposit that is covered by federal deposit insurance,” the FDIC said. Additionally, the FDIC said some banks incorrectly showed lower numbers “by excluding intercompany deposit balances of subsidiaries.” The FDIC declined to comment on specific banks.</p><p> The largest revision was by Bank of America. In a May 5 filing, Bank of America said its uninsured deposits were $784 billion as of Dec. 31, which was $125 billion, or 14%, less than it reported originally.</p><p> Unlike smaller banks, Bank of America was under little threat of mass withdrawals because it is widely believed the government wouldn&#39;t let the bank fail. But shifting the numbers could save Bank of America hundreds of millions of dollars.</p><p> In May, the FDIC said it <a href="https://www.wsj.com/livecoverage/stock-market-today-dow-jones-05-11-2023/card/banks-with-lots-of-uninsured-deposits-would-replenish-fdic-fund-under-new-proposal-Yjsqv5trBsXbXzuTTeCd?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">would impose a special assessment</a> on banks with more than $5 billion of total assets to cover the $15.8 billion that it cost to guarantee uninsured deposits at Silicon Valley Bank and <a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/SBNY" class="company-name">Signature Bank</a> after <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/signature-bank-is-shut-by-regulators-after-svb-failure-a5f9e0f7?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">they failed in March</a> . The assessment would be based on a bank&#39;s uninsured deposits as of Dec. 31. </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          inline
"><img width="600" height="800" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-823004?width=600" alt="不明确的" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><p> Based on the special-assessment formula proposed by the FDIC, Bank of America would owe $1.96 billion over two years using its revised Dec. 31 figure, down from $2.27 billion using its previously reported figure.</p><p> Bank of America spokesman William Haldin said the bank stands by its revised number. He said the bank had removed some internal or intra-bank accounts from its uninsured-deposit number and doesn&#39;t intend to file another revision.</p><p> The next-largest revision was by Huntington National Bank, a unit of Huntington Bancshares. In a May 26 filing, Huntington said its uninsured deposits were $51 billion as of Dec. 31, which was $34 billion, or 40%, less than it previously reported. Huntington, too, would realize significant savings on its special assessment if it were using its revised Dec. 31 number.</p><p> Huntington spokeswoman Tracy Pesho said: “Huntington National Bank restated its uninsured deposit levels to more accurately reflect customer deposits and exclude intercompany cash balances, consistent with other banks and our understanding of the FDIC&#39;s then-current instructions.” She said Huntington is “assessing the statement from the FDIC and determining what the appropriate next steps are.” </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="467" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-822610?width=700&amp;height=467" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> In a late May filing, Huntington National Bank lowered by 40% the amount of uninsured deposits as stated at the end of 2022.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Emily Elconin/Bloomberg News</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> In addition to restating uninsured deposits in past reports, other banks changed their definition to reduce them in current reports.</p> <a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/BOH" class="company-name">Bank of Hawaii</a> in its first-quarter filing with the FDIC showed a 20% drop in uninsured deposits to $8.7 billion, or 42% of total deposits, from $10.8 billion as of the fourth quarter. The main difference was the March 31 deposit number excluded collateralized deposits—a method the FDIC said was unacceptable.<p></p><p> Coincidentally, the bank reported second-quarter earnings Monday. It said its insured and collateralized deposits represented 61% of total deposit balances, up from 58% as of March 31, 2023 and 57% as of June 30, 2022. It didn&#39;t include a figure for uninsured deposits. A Bank of Hawaii spokesman didn&#39;t respond to a request for comment.</p><p> “When you see a small regional bank like Bank of Hawaii that has a sizable amount of deposits that are uninsured, that&#39;s real counterparty risk for the largely corporate depositors that are putting their trust in Bank of Hawaii,” said Brian Pillmore, founder and chief executive officer of Visbanking, which provides data and analysis on US banks.</p><p> Write to Jonathan Weil at <a href="mailto:jonathan.weil@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">jonathan.weil@wsj.com</a> and Shane Shifflett at <a href="mailto:shane.shifflett@dowjones.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">shane.shifflett@dowjones.com</a> </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          inline
"><iframe width="300" height="300" src="https://graphics.wsj.com/dynamic-inset-iframer/?url=https://asset.wsj.net/wsjnewsgraphics/projects/narrator/89390b44-9107-4a43-9db3-d54a5d5e65de.json" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe></div></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Mon, 24 Jul 2023 21:21:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/fdic-scolds-banks-for-manipulating-deposit-data-f7fe93d7</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/fdic-scolds-banks-for-manipulating-deposit-data-f7fe93d7<author><![CDATA[Jonathan WeilShane Shifflett]]></author><category>华尔街日报财经</category><category>wsjfinance-rer</category><category> Banking</category><category> Commercial Banking</category><category> Banking/Credit</category><category>金融服务</category><category>International Banks</category><category>企业/行业新闻</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category> Huntington Bancshares</category><category> HBAN</category><category> Bank of America</category><category> BAC</category><category> Bank of Hawaii</category><category> BOH</category><category>公司的</category><category>行业新闻</category><category>banking</category><category> commercial banking</category><category> credit</category><category>金融服务</category><category>international banks</category></item></channel></rss>